<paragraph id="755D36A03121FFC6FEFDFC100C55FC33" blockId="7.[262,526,908,930]" box="[262,526,908,930]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">
<heading id="2E1581CC3121FFC6FEFDFC100C55FC33" box="[262,526,908,930]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" reason="2">
<taxonomicName id="B2E24D233121FFC6FEFDFC100C55FC33" authority="Crotch" box="[262,526,908,930]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridana">
<emphasis id="4796EAB23121FFC6FEFDFC100C55FC33" bold="true" box="[262,526,908,930]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis id="4796EAB23121FFC6FEFDFC100F9AFC33" bold="true" box="[262,449,908,930]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Mantura floridana</emphasis>
Crotch
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="755D36A03121FFC6FF54FC2B0FA5F9DB" blockId="7.[151,639,951,1610]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">
<bibRefCitation id="11734B513121FFC6FF54FC2B0F04FC5D" author="Clark" box="[175,351,951,972]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" refId="ref6576" refString="Clark, S. M., D. G. LeDoux, T. N. Seeno, E. G. Riley, A. J. Gilbert, and J. M. Sullivan. 2004. Host plants of leaf beetle species occurring in the United States and Canada (Coleoptera: Megalopodidae, Orsodacnidae, Chrysomelidae, excluding Bruchinae). Coleopterists Society Special Publication No. 2." type="book" year="2004">
Clark 
<emphasis id="4796EAB23121FFC6FF11FC2B0F4FFC5D" box="[234,276,951,972]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">et al</emphasis>
. (2004)
</bibRefCitation>
state that this beetle normally feeds on species of 
<taxonomicName id="B2E24D233121FFC6FEB0FC4E0FD0FC76" box="[331,395,978,999]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Rumex" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4796EAB23121FFC6FEB0FC4E0FD0FC76" box="[331,395,978,999]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Rumex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName id="B2E24D233121FFC6FE4BFC4E0C6DFC76" box="[432,566,978,999]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Polygonaceae</taxonomicName>
), with a single record on another polygonaceous plant, 
<taxonomicName id="B2E24D233121FFC6FF6CFB9B0F32FB8D" box="[151,361,1031,1052]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="perfoliata">
<emphasis id="4796EAB23121FFC6FF6CFB9B0F32FB8D" box="[151,361,1031,1052]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Persicaria perfoliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) H. Gross. That record referred to adults, which were found only rarely on this host—more rarely than the legume-feeder 
<taxonomicName id="B2E24D233121FFC6FDDDFBA00FB3FBFD" authority="(Wheeler and Mengel 1984)" baseAuthorityName="Wheeler and Mengel" baseAuthorityYear="1984" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Odontota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dorsalis">
<emphasis id="4796EAB23121FFC6FDDDFBA00EBBFBFD" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Odontota dorsalis</emphasis>
(Wheeler and Mengel 1984)
</taxonomicName>
—so this cannot be considered a definite larval host. 
<bibRefCitation id="11734B513121FFC6FE22FBED0C26FB17" author="Clark" box="[473,637,1137,1158]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" refId="ref6576" refString="Clark, S. M., D. G. LeDoux, T. N. Seeno, E. G. Riley, A. J. Gilbert, and J. M. Sullivan. 2004. Host plants of leaf beetle species occurring in the United States and Canada (Coleoptera: Megalopodidae, Orsodacnidae, Chrysomelidae, excluding Bruchinae). Coleopterists Society Special Publication No. 2." type="book" year="2004">
Clark 
<emphasis id="4796EAB23121FFC6FDEBFBED0C6CFB17" box="[528,567,1137,1158]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">et al</emphasis>
. (2004)
</bibRefCitation>
list several other reported plant associations but consider them unusual, and apparently none of these refer to larval hosts. On 
<date id="015C10603121FFC6FEAFFB5D0F96FB47" box="[340,461,1217,1238]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" value="2013-06-08">8 June 2013</date>
, I found larvae of 
<taxonomicName id="B2E24D233121FFC6FF6CFB400F50FB60" box="[151,267,1244,1265]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridana">
<emphasis id="4796EAB23121FFC6FF6CFB400F50FB60" box="[151,267,1244,1265]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">M. floridana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mining leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="B2E24D233121FFC6FE55FB400C0DFB60" box="[430,598,1244,1265]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Fallopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="scandens">
<emphasis id="4796EAB23121FFC6FE55FB400C0DFB60" box="[430,598,1244,1265]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Fallopia scandens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) Holub (
<taxonomicName id="B2E24D233121FFC6FF21FB6A0F00FA9A" box="[218,347,1270,1291]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Polygonaceae</taxonomicName>
) in Belchertown, 
<collectingRegion id="B726F8423121FFC6FE0EFB6A0C20FA9A" box="[501,635,1270,1291]" country="United States of America" name="Massachusetts" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Massachusetts</collectingRegion>
. The mines were whitish and serpentine, on the upper leaf surface, with frass in irregular dark lumps and strings. In one case, 
<specimenCount id="63E4FD293121FFC6FE9FFADA0F96FACA" box="[356,461,1350,1371]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" type="larva">four larvae</specimenCount>
were mining in a single leaf (
<figureCitation id="EDD92A253121FFC6FEFBFAFC0F18FAE4" box="[256,323,1376,1397]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[175,215,1614,1633]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,698,1591]" captionTargetId="figure-285@5.[151,1172,698,1592]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 13–17. 13) Young Sumitrosis inaequalis larva mining in white wood aster (Eurybia divaricata) leaf; egg at upper right; 14) Mine of Sumitrosis rosea in leaf of Oriental bittersweet (Celastrus orbiculatus); 15) Detail of presumed Dibolia chelones mine in leaf of white turtlehead (Chelone glabra), showing squiggly strings of frass; 16) Leaf of climbing false buckwheat (Fallopia scandens) mined by four Mantura floridana larvae; 17) Mines of Monoxia angularis in Atriplex prostrata leaf." pageId="7" pageNumber="358">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). They were able to exit and establish additional mines in new leaves. On 9 June, a wandering larva burrowed into soil the instant it was given the opportunity. I was unable to observe the larvae again until 15 June, when I returned home and could see one of them in a cell constructed in the soil against the side of the glass jar. This larva pupated within the next day, and at least 
<specimenCount id="63E4FD293121FFC6FDDAF9860C26F9BE" box="[545,637,1562,1583]" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" type="adult">four adult</specimenCount>
<taxonomicName id="B2E24D233121FFC6FF6CF9A90F57F9DB" box="[151,268,1589,1610]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mantura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridana">
<emphasis id="4796EAB23121FFC6FF6CF9A90F57F9DB" box="[151,268,1589,1610]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="358">M. floridana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had emerged by 23 June.
</paragraph>
